  "doc_id": "15584",
  "text": "Modeling studies have addressed the thalamic role in anesthetic-induced hypnosis [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . In a study modeling human sleep, propofol-induced GABA A activation promoted thalamic involvement and cortical synchronization. Interestingly, the reticular nucleus of the thalamus, which sends prominent GABAergic projections to other thalamic nuclei, was able to synchronize disparate relay nuclei and thus, facilitate cortical synchronization over large areas of cortex [CITATION_3] . This study suggests that propofol may induce hypnosis, at least in part, by acting on the thalamus.",
